Here, $A$ denotes the overall circuit gain (distinct from the basic op amp's gain $a(\rightarrow \infty)$). Since $v_{O}$ shares the same polarity as $v_{I}$, the circuit is termed a noninverting amplifier.
- The Inverting Amplifier: In the circuit shown in Fig. $1.28 b$, the op amp influences $v_{N}$ through the feedback resistor $R_{2}$. Given that the op amp rule states $v_{N}=v_{P}=0$, node $v_{N}$ is considered a virtual ground. Any current introduced by $v_{I}$ through $R_{1}$ is counteracted by $v_{O}$ through $R_{2}$, meaning $i_{1}=i_{2}$. Applying Ohm's law,
$$
\frac{v_{I}-0}{R_{1}}=\frac{0-v_{O}}{R_{2}}
$$
Solving for the ratio $v_{O} / v_{I}$ results in
$$
\begin{equation*}
A=\frac{v_{O}}{v_{I}}=-\frac{R_{2}}{R_{1}} \tag{1.12}
\end{equation*}
$$
Due to the opposite polarity of $v_{O}$ relative to $v_{I}$, the circuit is known as an inverting amplifier.
- The Summing Amplifier: According to the op amp rule, the inverting-input node in Fig. 1.29 is at virtual ground. This node acts as a summing junction, combining the currents from input sources $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ and directing this sum to the output node $v_{O}$, leading to
$$
\frac{v_{1}-0}{R_{1}}+\frac{v_{2}-0}{R_{2}}=\frac{0-v_{0}}{R_{3}}
$$
Solving for $v_{o}$,
$$
\begin{equation*}
v_{O}=-\left(\frac{R_{3}}{R_{1}} v_{1}+\frac{R_{3}}{R_{2}} v_{2}\right) \tag{1.13}
\end{equation*}
$$
If $R_{1}=R_{2}$, the circuit produces $v_{O}=-\left(R_{3} / R_{1}\right)\left(v_{1}+v_{2}\right)$ and is appropriately called a summing amplifier.
- The Voltage Buffer: By setting $R_{2}=0$ and $R_{1}=\infty$ in the circuit of Fig. $1.28 a$, it becomes a unity-gain amplifier $(A=1 \mathrm{~V} / \mathrm{V})$. Its primary use is as a voltage buffer to prevent inter-stage loading. For instance, consider Fig. 1.30a, where a signal
