- The Inverting Amplifier: In the circuit shown in Fig. $1.28 b$, the op amp influences $v_{N}$ through the feedback resistor $R_{2}$. Given that the op amp rule dictates $v_{N}=v_{P}=0$, node $v_{N}$ is deemed a virtual ground. Any current introduced by $v_{I}$ through $R_{1}$ is counteracted by $v_{O}$ through $R_{2}$, meaning $i_{1}=i_{2}$. Applying Ohm's law,
$$
\frac{v_{I}-0}{R_{1}}=\frac{0-v_{O}}{R_{2}}
$$
Solving for the ratio $v_{O} / v_{I}$ yields
$$
\begin{equation*}
A=\frac{v_{O}}{v_{I}}=-\frac{R_{2}}{R_{1}} \tag{1.12}
\end{equation*}
$$
Due to the opposite polarity of $v_{O}$ relative to $v_{I}$, the circuit is known as an inverting amplifier.
- The Summing Amplifier: According to the op amp rule, the inverting-input node in Fig. 1.29 is at virtual ground. This node acts as a summing junction, combining the currents from input sources $v_{1}$ and $v_{2}$ and directing this sum to the output node $v_{O}$, resulting in
$$
\frac{v_{1}-0}{R_{1}}+\frac{v_{2}-0}{R_{2}}=\frac{0-v_{0}}{R_{3}}
$$
Solving for $v_{o}$,
$$
\begin{equation*}
v_{O}=-\left(\frac{R_{3}}{R_{1}} v_{1}+\frac{R_{3}}{R_{2}} v_{2}\right) \tag{1.13}
\end{equation*}
$$
When $R_{1}=R_{2}$, the circuit produces $v_{O}=-\left(R_{3} / R_{1}\right)\left(v_{1}+v_{2}\right)$ and is fittingly called a summing amplifier.
